{
  "answer": "**Sicily.**\n\nIn \"Saqaliya\" from *Bang-e-Dara Part 2* (Chapter 21), Allama Iqbal directly addresses Sicily as the site of a lost Muslim (\"Hejazi\") civilization, lamenting its ruins and former glory under Islamic rule (referencing Arab conquests there from 827–1091 CE). The poem personifies the island, calling it \"the honor of the sea\" and \"the cradle of that nation's culture,\" while evoking its historical role in Islamic history.[^1][^2]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, \"Saqaliya\" [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/21-saqaliya/translation/#p-379aeb).\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, \"Saqaliya\" [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/21-saqaliya/translation/#p-08760e).",
